<paragraph blockId="32.[212,1445,1791,1850]" lastBlockId="33.[242,1474,266,394]" lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="132" pageId="32" pageNumber="131">
DESCRIPTION. — Apart from the characters in the key distinguishing this species from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevrolat" authorityYear="1877" box="[1155,1313,1792,1815]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Elytrocallus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montrouzieri">
<emphasis box="[1155,1313,1792,1815]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="131">E. montrouzieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, males of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Montrouzier" baseAuthorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Elytrocallus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lapeyrousei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="131">E. lapeyrousei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the suture, margins and two oblique bands on elytra white, leaving three areas black, the first two of these usually containing metallic pink scales; females have chalky white elytra with fine transverse rugosities or lines on the dorsum, sometimes with a lateral pink spot behind the shoulders and one or two spots dorsally near the shoulders.
</paragraph>
